For further details, including a transcript and translation, see Jon Pepper, 'Harriot's calculation of the meridional parts as logarithimic tangents', Archive for History of Exact Sciences, 4(1968), 359–413 (pages 366–367, and 411–413). Quod rumbus in planispærio nostro facit angulum cum meridiano æqualem angulo facto a rumbo cum meridiano in sphæera. That a rhumb in our planisphere makes an angle with the meridian equal to the angle made by the rhumb with the meridian on the sphere.
0033.jpg 17r 33 JS Sept 24, 2013 Quod rumbus in planispærio nostro facit angulum cum meridiano æqualem angulo facto a rumbo cum meridiano in sphæera. That a rhumb in our planisphere makes an angle with the meridian equal to the angle made by the rhumb with the meridian on the sphere. Sit $ ABE $ semicirculus pro meridiano quolibet in globo terrestri. Cuius centrum $ e $. poli $ A $ et $ E $. Sit, $ e X $, communis sectio æquatoris et plani meridiani, quæ meridianus est in nostro planisphærio correlatiuus meridiano in globo terrestri. In semicirculo pro meridiano sumatur quodvis punctum $ B $. Agatur recta $ AB $ producta quæ secabit, $ eX $, in puncto $ b $, et punctum $ b $ in planisphærio erit correllatium puncto $ B $ in superficie sphæræ. Agatur etiam recta, $ e B $, et $ GH $ tangens peripheriam in puncto, $ B $. Dico primo quod anguli $ HBb $ et $ HbB $ sunt æquales. $ HBb + ABe = $ recto. $ ebA + eAB = $ recto. Ergo: $ HBb + ABe = ebA + eAB $. Sed: $ ABe = eAB $. ergo: $ HBb = HbB $. Let $ ABE $ be a semicircle on any meridian of the terrestrial sphere, with centre $ e $, and poles $ A $ and $ E $. Let $ eX $ be the intersection of the equator and the meridional plane, which meridian in our planisphere corresponds to the meridian in the terrestrial sphere. In the semicircle take any point $ B $ on the meridian. Construct the extended line $ AB $ which will cut $ eX $ in the point $ b $, and the point $ b $ in the planisphere will correspond to the point $ B $ on the surface of the sphere. Also construct the lines $ eB $ and $ GH $ touching the circumference in the point $ B $. I say first that the angles $ HBb $ amd $ HbB $ are equal. $ HBb + ABe = $ a right angle. $ ebA + eAB = $ a right angle. Therefore $ HBb + ABe = ebA + eAB $. But $ ABe = eAB $. Therefore $ HBb = HbB $.
0033.jpg 17r 33 JS Sept 24, 2103 Quod rumbus in planispærio nostro facit angulum cum meridiano æqualem angulo facto a rumbo cum meridiano in sphæera. That a rhumb in our planisphere makes an angle with the meridian equal to the angle made by the rhumb with the meridian on the sphere. Iam intelligitur $ B $ punctum esse centrum circuli nautici qui vulgo compassus dicitur; sive circuli horizontis visibilis. cuius plano $ eB $, est ad angulos rectos. $ GH $ est communis sectio plani meridiani et circuli nautici, et est linea dicta meridiana in plano . Agatur linea $ BD $ faciens angulum $ DBG $ et in illa linea sumatur quodvis punctum $ D $ et Agatur $ DC $ perpendicularis ad $ GH $. Conectantur puncta $ AC $: et $ AD $. et constituatur pyramis cuius basis $ BCD $, et vertex, $ A $. Quoniam $ CD $, perpendicularis est in plano erecto ad planum meridionis circuli productum erit etiam perpendicularis ad $ CA $, et planum trianguli $ DCA $ erit erectum ad planum meridiani. Linea $ AC $, secat, $ e X $, in puncto $ c $ (non opus est ducere lineas $ DF $, et $ CF $. ideo omittuntur). Now it is to be understood that the point $ B $ is the centre of a nautical circle, which is commonly called the compass; or circle of the visible horizon, which is at right angles to the plane of $ eB $. $ GH $ is common to the plane of the meridian and that nautical circle and is said to be the meridional line in the horizontal plane. Construct any line $ BD $ in the horizontal plane making any angle $ DBG $ with the meridian $ BG $ and in that lane take any point $ D $, and construct $ DC $ perpendicular to $ GH $. Join the points $ AC $ and $ AD $ to make a pyramid whose base is $ BCD $ and vertex $ A $. Since $ CD $ is a perpendicular in a plane at right angles to the plane of the circle of the meridion, it is also perpendicular to $ CA $, and the plane of triangle $ DCA $ will be at right angles to the plane of the meridian. The line $ AC $ cuts $ e X $ in the point $ c $. (there is no need to draw the lines $ DF $ and $ CF $, therefore they are omitted).

0055.jpg 28r 55 mschemmel 30.09.2013 This is the first of a sequence of paginated pages on which Harriot explores what may be called the inclined-plane conception of projectile motion, see (Schemmel 2008, Chapter 8). According to this conception, projectile motion is composed of a decelerated motion in the oblique direction of the shot, and an accelerated motion of vertical fall. The dependence of the oblique motion on the angle of projection corresponds to that of a motion along an inclined plane on the angle of inclination. More specifically, the page is part of Harriot’s introduction of compound diagrams of motion, a group of folios on which Harriot eventually succeeds in deriving, by means of such diagrams, a general expression for the time of flight of a projectile (Schemmel 2008, Section 8.2). On this particular page, Harriot demonstrates that the spaces traversed by two motions along planes of different inclination, ending at the same degree of velocity, as well as the times needed to traverse them, stand in inverse proportion to the degrees of the two motions taken at some arbitrary point in time. 1.) For oblique motions.

0087.jpg 44r 87 JS Jun 1, 2012 The reference to Bernardus Tornius Florentinus is to his commentary on De motu locali of William Heytesbury (c. 1313–1372/3). The text of Tornius is found as the seventh treatise in William Heytesbury, De sensu composito et diviso (Tornius 1494) , 73v–77v. The reference to Alvarus Thomas is to his Liber de triplici motu (Thomas 1509) . The texts of both Alvarus and Tornius are verbal, expressed in terms of repeated proportions. Harriot converts their results into arithmetic notation, and in doing so shows how to find sums of some infinite series that are not simple geometric progressions. His first example (from Tornius) is $ \frac{2}{3} + \frac{4}{9} + \frac{6}{27} + \frac{8}{81} + \dots = \frac{3}{2} $. Harriot shows how this can be treated as the sum of infinitely many other series, each of which is a simple geometric progression, namely: $ \frac{2}{3} + \frac{2}{9} + \frac{2}{27} + \frac{2}{81} + \dots = 1 $, $ \frac{2}{9} + \frac{2}{27} + \frac{2}{81} + \dots = \frac{1}{3} $, $ \frac{2}{27} + \frac{2}{81} + \dots = \frac{1}{9} $, $ \dots $. The sums of these series form a new geometric progression $ 1 + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{9} + \dots = 1\frac{1}{2} $. The other two series on the page (from Alvarus) are summed in the same way.

0367.jpg 184r 367 rg Sep 26, 2013 This page is part of Harriot's experiments on refractive colours. Summary of Harriot's analysis of colour experiments with glass and water-filled prisms. The large diagram shows the geometrical construction for the 58° glass prism, and throughout the pages on both the glass and the water prism, this construction and its associated lettering are implicit. Despite the title and the depiction of the glass prism, Harriot's summary here includes the water prism. The pair of "cardinals" he discovers for each substance ("vitri cardinales" and "aquae cardinales") indicate, in effect, the range of refractive indices that direct light passing through these substances towards either the red or yellow. 0779.jpg 390r 779 RG 2015-03-20 This page is part of Harriot's treatment of burning mirrors, specifically, the concave spherical mirror. Calculation of place where a ray of light, incident parallel to the axis of a spherical mirror, cuts the axis after reflection. Harriot's source is almost certainly (della Porta 1593, 40-41), where della Porta proved that ray $EF$ (in Harriot's diagram) is reflected to point $G$, and $G$ is found at the interception of the perpendicular bisector $IG$ to the radius of the mirror $CF$, and the axis. Harriot follows della Porta's construction precisely in the first part of this sheet, omitting della Porta's geometrical proof; but he adds (after the heading "Aliter") a trigonometrical version of the construction, which he will use as a means of calculation throughout the pages on the spherical mirror. I fell since into Vieta's last probleme of his second apendicle Apol: Gal: and compared his way with yours that you last gave me: but to confesse a truth I can have my will of neither; and the probleme appeares to me not universall but requires determination. for let the, $ ba $ given, have the same sides, $ ab $. $ ac $. that Vieta's hath and lett, $ v' $, $ s'' $. be the same that Vieta gives; now I will give a, $ \Delta $ that shall have thos sides, so it shalbe impossible to finde anie pointe, from whence lines drawen unto the corners be in the given rate. and that is by givein a, $ \Delta $. with the same sides $ ab $. $ ac $. but such as the $ bac $ $ > $ or $ &lt; $ then Vieta's $ bac $. in such measure as Vieta's two circles doe neither cut nor touch. this rubbe put me out of this course. whereuppon I betooke me to your problemes for the distinguishinge of the sides of $ \Delta $ whether the summe or difference of the sides and the angle adjacente or contained with the other side were given. in this I proceed still with much pleasure and satisfaction. I have also putt in order all thos propositions which you also gave me, but I had copied in lose papers & with ill diagrammes so that all those thinges stand well and so I thanke god doe we also. Excepte my catle which have all this winter been persecuted wiht the Murraine. since Christmas verie neare I have lost, 100. beasts; Vieta's sacrifice for the invention of our probleme. but I scarce keepe my promise with you. farewell. I am all yours. Willm. Lower.

0881.jpg 441r 881 Three reasons to prove that there is a passage from the Northwest into the South sea.
0881.jpg 441r 881 1. The tydes in Port Nelson (where S Tho: Button did winter) move constantly. 15, or. 18. foote; which is not found in any Bays Throughout the world but in such seas as lie open att both ends to the mayne Ocean.
0881.jpg 441r 881 2. Every strong westerne winde did bring into the Harbor where he wintered, so much water, that the Neap-tydes were æquall to the Spring-tydes, notwithstanding that the Harbor was open only to the E. N. E.
0881.jpg 441r 881 3. In coming out of the harbor, shaping his course, directly North, about, 60, degrees, he found a strong race of a tyde, setting due East & West, which in probabilitie could be noe other thing, than the tyde coming from the West, and retourning from the East.

0923.jpg 462r 923 Of Architecture SWL In building there is this rule præscribed by architectes that the second story is in hight $ \frac{3}{4} $ of the first, & the third $ \frac{3}{4} $ of the second.
0923.jpg 462r 923 Of Architecture SWL The reason is: supposing the first to be Doricke with his complements . The second must be Ionicke. And then understand that the base of the pedistall of the Ionicke be æquall to the diameter of the Doricke base, because solid must be upon solid, & then the rest of the Ionicke worke in proportion will make the sayd $ \frac{3}{4} $.
0923.jpg 462r 923 Of Architecture SWL The third must be Corinthian. & the base of his pedistall must be æquall to the diameter of the Ionick piller & the rest with the complements will also bringe forth the sayd $ \frac{3}{4} $.

1051.jpg 527r 1051 Out of Sr Walter Copes Apology For the Earle of Salisbury Treasureship. He found dates of 3 or 400,000, to the King, what were separate what desperate no man knew. he sought for better knowledge. He caused the K. Mannors to be surveyed. The K. custodye landes anciently called the crowne landes conserved in the pipe. The decayed revenues he retained by the K. commission of Assertes. He caused the K. woodes to be surveyed. He raysed the K. revenues, out of the copyholders for . Coppyholders inheritance. Mastes & commons Casuall fines. extended lands surveyed. He improved the customs, & advanced them from 86,000 to 120,000. & from 120,000 to 135,000 per anum. He got money for the K. from the dealers in Allome. By his for the Baronets hath brought into the K. coffers 80,000. By his bargayne for bringing water to London likely to bring in great yearly reveneu to the K. He was a patron of all Industry & manufactures, of there & intentions. As for the of Allum, of Buffes, for fishing, Copper & copperall of Iron & steele, sault by the home, sault upon salt, & men farmers & fiers for easy workmanship.
1051.jpg 527r 1051 Out of Sr Walter Copes Apology For the Earle of Salisbury concerning his secretarys place &c. & concerning the wardes &c. I note nothing.
1051.jpg 527r 1051 Out of Sr Walter Copes Apology For the Earle of Salisbury out of his answere to obiections Queen Mary raysed cloth from 14 to a noble. The Gascoigne wines from 3 to 4 markes. Queen Elizab. raysed the sweet wines from 3 6 to 40 the tonne. And upon the currents for every 5 hundred 5 6. He forebeare to impose upon & all natures incident to the poore & upon all thinges concerning the ordinance, shippes, & defence of the realme but imposed specially upon silkes, spices, lawnes, cambrickes, whale bones & such like thinges rather of dilicacy then necessity, allowing free liberty to transport without charge what was not vented here.

1052.jpg 527v 1052 out of Sr Water Copes booke intituled: Certayne breefe remonstrances offerd to his Ma. &c. 1613. * The seas & Merchant only ever to before & therefore the stat: 13 of Eliz. The Marchant only hath power passe & returne wihout licence.
1052.jpg 527v 1052 out of Sr Water Copes booke intituled: Certayne breefe remonstrances offerd to his Ma. &c. 1613. Towardes the latter end concerning Busses for fishing. Anno 1611 it so far proceeded that after long consultation we framed a body for the corporation consisting of a Governor a deputy, a Treasurer, 24 consulls, 24 assistantes, a sercher, a Guager, &c. with free liberty to all that would become adventurers. We then agreed that the Government should be generall for matters of order, particular for matter of adventure, having ever at liberty to venture for itself. We then agreed of lawes and ordinances for the generall company at under & the particular companyes in the country that there might an æquall correspondence between them all. We then agreed of 19 privileges that might give & comfort to all the undertakers. But when we came to the and that the end should have crowned the work, when we came to the 17th privilege which made it lawfull to carry our fish & returne commodityes from all partes whatsoever notwithstanding all former privilege to the contrary. All the companyes (especially the Adventurers) strongly opposed it as if they should want commodityes for there & our return we then offered them to make them parteners of our corpo- ration which they refused. We then demanded whether they wold make us in worse case then the Hollanders who vented there great masse of fish in all partes of the world, & made there returns home & better at there pleasures. They answered that returnes into Holland did them no hurt, Returnes into England might undo their great trade of cloth. And upon this uncharitable, uniust, & idle proposition, what should become of our fish, before either Busses builded or nettes made or fish taken; this great & noble worke of the Busses hath for these 2 yeares ben last layd or asleep. I call it uniust & uncharitable because agaynst the great Cha & agaynst many other lawes of this realme. Agaynst the birthright & freedom of every subject. And against all leagues & treatyes of states. As appeares in the treaty of Bruxelles the 24. Jan. 1515. between Cha prince of Spayne & Henry 8. K. of England. And agaynst their second treaty April. 11. 1520. betweene Charles the first then Emperor & our & alos agaynst a third treaty 1529. and contrary to our privileges granted by the hosue of Burgundy & by the Emperor of Moscovy &c. In all which is allowed for the K. and all his subjects to come & to go to buy to sell by land by sea in all clymes partes creekes &c. in free liberall & ample manner as the very natives of his crowne kingdom without exception or restraynt in favour of the Adventurers or any company whatsoever. All lawes & treatyes ever ayming after liberty of trade. * above. (No more I noted.)

1065.jpg 534r 1065 1. Of the manner to observe the variation of compasse, or of the wires of the same, by the sonnes rising or setting.
1065.jpg 534r 1065 1. Of the manner to observe the variation of compasse, or of the wires of the same, by the sonnes rising or setting. There are two sortes of compasse ordayned for of the wires; one hath a moveable fly; the other hath none. The or north poynt of the fly standeth directly with the wires in both. And the utmost circle of both is devided in to poynts & degrees; there being 11 degrees & a quarter betwixt poynte & poynte. Then for your observat- on you are to do as followeth.
1065.jpg 534r 1065 1. Of the manner to observe the variation of compasse, or of the wires of the same, by the sonnes rising or setting. In morning or eveninge when you may see the sonne rise or set (your compasse standing fit;) you are to marke degrees the sonne riseth from the East poynt of the fly; or setteth from the west, & note whether to the southwardes or northwards; this observation & as many as you can make enter into your booke; noting the day & place you made it.
1065.jpg 534r 1065 1. Of the manner to observe the variation of compasse, or of the wires of the same, by the sonnes rising or setting. Then for the finding of the variation, I have calculated a speciall table for the purpose; whose title is A table for the sonne rising & setting from the true East & West. which you are to use in this manner. first consider what declination the sonne hath that present day which you know by your Regiment; Also what is the elevation of the pole at that plane, which you are to know upon reckoning from your last observation.
1065.jpg 534r 1065 1. Of the manner to observe the variation of compasse, or of the wires of the same, by the sonnes rising or setting. Then in the sayd table of thes onnes rising & setting loke in the head of the table the degrees of the sonnes declination; & on the side loke the Degree of elevation & right agaynst the same under the declination you efore noted; (in the common angle) you shall find how much the sonne riseth or setteth from the true east or west in degrees & minuts. rising is always to the northward if the sonne hath north declination, or southward if the declination be south. And this nomber of degrees & minuts for brevity sake hereafter to be used is called the sonnes Amplitude.
1065.jpg 534r 1065 1. Of the manner to observe the variation of compasse, or of the wires of the same, by the sonnes rising or setting. Now to conclude how much your compasse doth vary the breefest & most intelligible way is this: note upon the same fly you made your observation by, or upon any other in any booke that hath degrees in the utmost circle, the degree that the prime rose be set upon: Then from that marke reckon or nomber the degrees of the sonnes Amplitude northward if the sonne hath south declination; or reckon southward if the sonne hath north declination & where the degrees end there is the true east or west; which being had, it is then manifest both how much your compasse doth vary & which way.
1066.jpg 534v 1066
1067.jpg 535r 1067 2.
1067.jpg 535r 1067 2. one Example will make this playne. Suppose you be to the southward of the Lysard & in the syght of 48 degrees the 10 of February next this year 1595. And that you find the sonne to rise 7 degrees to the southwards of the East by such a compasse as hath the wires doe move.
1067.jpg 535r 1067 2. Then loke in the sonnes regiment & you shall find the decli- nation of the sonne for that 10th day at noon 1595 to be $ 10.58' $ south. you may see that the day before it was more by $ 21' $. & there- fore that morning it ought to be more by quarter of $ 21' $ which is $ 5' $. & therefore the declinatin of the sonne at that present time is $ 11.3' $. but a few minuts in this would not be regarded but you may take the declination as you finde it at noone that day, which you may 11 degrees & because it cometh thereunto.
1067.jpg 535r 1067 2. Then in the table of the sonnes rising & setting, right agaynst the hight of 48 degrees & under the declination of 11. deg. you shall find 15 degrees & 33 minuts which is the amplitude of the sonnes rising from the true East And to be southwards of the east so much because the sonne had south declination.
1067.jpg 535r 1067 2. Now marke upon the compasse upon what degrees the sonne rose; then reckon from it northward according to your rule, because the sonne hath such a decli- nation, the nomber of 16 degrees & a half; & you shall find them to end 9 degrees & a half to the north- wardes of the East of the compasse. And so much doth the true east vary or differre from that of your compasse. And so per consequence all the poyntes else from that truth. That is to says the East of your compasse doth vary 9 degrees & a half to the southwardes from the truth; And therefore the north of your compasse so much to the Eastwards; The South poynt to the westwards And your west poynt to the Northwards. But of what poynts so ever you register in your booke the variation, you must specially note the variation of the North poynt, becasue it is the cheefest poynt in name, & all the rest wilbe ordered by it.
1068.jpg 535v 1068
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3.
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. And Because the stirradge is made commonly by the common compasse whose wires stand half a poynt to the Eastwards of the North of the fly. It is necessary that you also know the variation of this compasse, otherwise sayling by such a compasse, you can make no reckoning of your course, nor appoynt what stirradge ought to be made.
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. therefore geve this severall rule: having noted the variation of the wires or north poynt the former compasses which some call Meridionall compasses; you shall find the variation of the north poynt of the common compasse thus: ;
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. ffirst in that compasse that hath the moveable fly; move it in such sort that his north poynt stand to the northward of the wires half a poynt; then must the wires be to the east- wards so much, & so that fly representeth the common compasse;
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. After reckon the degrees of your former variation from the wires contrary to the denomination; that is to say if the variation were East, reckon northward; or if west reckon Eastward & where the degrees ened there is the true north of the world; which being marked you may then see both hos much & which way the North of the fly or common compasse doth vary.
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. You may also do the same by that compasse which hath no moveable fly, or any other drawne in any booke so it be devided into degrees & that you make a pricke or note half a poynt to the westwards of the north represent the north of your common compasse.
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. But our compasse have no degrees you helpe your self by addition & subtraction, remembring that 11 degrees & a quarter make a poynt & 5 degrees & a half & half a quarter do make half a poynt.
1069.jpg 536r 1069 3. The example of this need be but short: The wires in the former observation varied to the eastward 9 degrees & a half. halfe a poynt to the northwards is the north of the common compasse; therefore abate it out $ 9\frac{1}{2} $. there will remayne 4 degrees nerest. & so much doth your common compasse vary in that plane; being lesse then half a poynt & to the eastwards as before bycause the half poynt was lesse then the variation of the wires.
1070.jpg 536v 1070
1071.jpg 537r 1071 4.
1071.jpg 537r 1071 4. But if half a poynt had been greater, then it had varied the contrary way by the differences. If the former rules be well understode there cannot happen any case concerning this variation, but you may very well know when to adde or subtracte & what is don by them, if you will use that means. you have your choyse; so that I need not be more tædiouse.
1071.jpg 537r 1071 4. This means of observing the variation of all others is most redy easy & certayne; the way that they use by observing the north starre is not true but only of 40 & 50 degrees because there only he is in the meridian or , which to all seamen is a paradox. & to affirme the starre by the compasse when he is hye is very uncertayne; but when he is it is a goode meanes to attayne to the variation nere hand neither do I wishe it to be refused, being under the hygh of 20 degrees. & at NE & SW guard. So likewise is it to be preferred before any single observation that is made of the sonne when they many degrees hye or any doble of the forenoone & afternoone; which are only goode at land where the horizon can not be seene & when this way can not be used of which way as others have written specially M w: Borrowes in his booke of the variation annexed to Normans new Attractions.
1071.jpg 537r 1071 4. Besides the benefit that it hath in shewing your true course, it will hereafter be a meanes to observe the longitude sufficiently exact, & therefore I wish it the more to be regarded.
1071.jpg 537r 1071 4. By the table also of the sonnes Amplitude with the rules before may be found the variation of the compasse by the moone or any starre whose inclination may be found in the table.
